employment was Normalized by the Establishment of Public Labour Exchanges in Austria, 1918–1938 -- t12 The Poor Unemployed: Diagnoses of Unemployment in Britain and West Germany in the 1970s and 1980s -- tIV. RE-ESTABLISHING SOCIAL TIES: NARRATIVES AND APPEALS FROM THE POOR -- t13 Voices from the Lower Depths: Russian Poor in Their Own Words -- t14 ‘They Sit for Days and Have Only Their Sorrow to Eat’: Old Age Poverty in German and British Pauper Narratives -- t15 Seen with Their Own Eyes: Self-presentation of the Poor in Freiburg and Schwerin, 1950–1975 -- tConclusion: The Twisted Paths of Recognition and Protection: Vulnerability and Welfare in European Societies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn many ways, the European welfare state constituted a response to the new forms of social fracture and economic turbulence that were born out of industrialization—challenges that were particularly acute for groups whose integration into society seemed the most tenuous. Covering a range of national cases, this volume explores the relationship of weak social ties to poverty and how ideas about this relationship informed welfare policies in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. By focusing on three representative populations—neglected children, the homeless, and the unemployed—it provides a rich, comparative consideration of the shifting perceptions, representations, and lived experiences of social vulnerability in modern Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aPoorzEuropexHistory. 0aPublic welfarezEuropexHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aAlthammer, Beate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlthammer, Beate, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vo